{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"99379e9d-30a6-41a1-9bd4-d2910fa25fd8","content":"Add a `.vscode/mcp.json` file to your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command`/`args`** — uses `dotnet run` so it builds and runs automatically.\n- If you publish a self-contained binary instead, point `command` directly at the executable.\n- Make sure your server reads from stdin and writes to stdout (the standard MCP stdio transport).\n\nAfter saving, restart VS Code or run **\"MCP: List Servers\"** from the command palette to verify it connects.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"38393e22-53e1-4596-920c-f10eb41270b2","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't actually exist yet, but the user is asking how to configure mcp.json. I can give them the configuration guidance directly.","outputTokens":268},"id":"f8e4eae7-84e2-4802-ba16-2b489889c748","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:48:19.870Z","parentId":"c86ee9bb-44b9-4d7e-b91b-1d3c254b9c28"}
